I have been watching F1 since Australia '95 and since then I missed only two races (both because of hospitalization periods).
I've always enjoyed following the sport even in its least interesting periods: I never backed off during the rather boring Schumi dominion era, I survived the Mercedes dominion era, I've even accepted the sport entering its Zoomer era. I can honestly say F1 is an integral part of my life. I've watched races with people who aren't alive anymore, I've gone to events with girls, I've shared my passion with many friends and family throught the years. I've never being a hardcore fan for one team or driver, I've always enjoyed the races as much as I could do regardless of the winners
The 2022 brazilian GP totally killed my interest. I can't say why but watching Russell on the top of the podium switched somethign off in my brain. This is the first year I'm not exceted for the presentation of the new cars, and I'm not excited for the season in general.

That sounds pretty reasonable. I think recent achievements tell a lot more about how a boxer fares than how they fought 10 years ago. After all we’re trying to determine who is the best active boxer, not who would hypothetically be the best in some kind of vague “prime”. I really think boxing is a sport of youre only as good as your last few fights. Not meant to be taken hyper literally and past achievements should be taken into account, but I find oftentimes people get hung up on the past to the point where they may gloss over whats weak or strong about a fighter’s most recent performance. Injuries, changes in tactics, stamina problems, so on and so forth. I like a more by the numbers type deal. Judging on technique alone only says so much, but at the same time I find we dont need to over scrutinize someone’s resume to the point of exhaustion. If you dont know the details surrounding the fight the outcome is on paper is not that helpful by itself. You need to explain how they won and what makes them better than everyone else.

The other problem with p4p lists is they dont really factor in styles. Some fighter might technically be ranked worse than another, maybe by a large margin, but because its a particularly bad matchup for the styles this sort of boosts one of the fighters. Boxing isnt so simple to give people numerical numbers.

I also dont think losses should count THAT badly against someone’s scores. Getting hung up on undefeated records is a meme. The greats of old rarely had undefeated records and the few who did it was because of an early retirement. When the best fight the best, someone loses. Thats why its important to understand the details of a fight. Simply saying this guy lost and this guy won doesnt mean a whole lot by itself.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128835051
Im glad you asked. It starts with having actually won a fight as the smaller guy
So that means no Luke Fury or anybody else (haney, josh taylor) who has only won fights against fighters with smaller frames than them
Then I look at the original 8 weight classes (fly, bantam, feather, light, welter, middle, light heavy, heavy) and see who the champions are and how they got there. 2 of these weight classes have Undisputed champions, but only one of those champions won a fight as the smaller guy so Inoue is pound for pound #1

Then I look at people that are nearly undisputed/3 belt champions. There are 3 of those in the original weight classes, Artur Beterbiev, Errol Spence, and Oleksandr Usyk. Both Beterbiev and Usyk win fights as the smaller guy, but a slight edge to Usyk puts him at #2 because of my next criteria

Achievements in the other (super/junior) weight classes
Usyk was undisputed at a lower weight class, whereas Beterbiev and Spence have spent their careers at the 1 weight class. This is also where fighters whose current achievements are in super/junior classes can be ranked, like Canelo and Jermell Charlo

Next we look for partial/unified champions in the other classes who win as the smaller fighter, so that's where you place Stephen Fulton and Kenshiro Teraji

And finally the "other factors" section, where you place original 8 fighters on hot streaks aka the eye test fighters, like Crawford and Bivol

1. Inoue
2. Usyk
3. Beterbiev
4. Spence
5. Canelo
6. Jermell Charlo
7. Fulton
8. Teraji
9. Crawford
10. Bivol

It's a complex science, and maybe even a bullshit one, but at the end of the day, 'pound-for-pound' is a concept that has been around since the SRR days, so it's a piece of boxing history whether you like it or not
For me personally...
1. The best way to gauge P4P greatness is a fighter winning big fights and/or belts in multiple divisions, as this shows they can close the size gap using sheer skill (i.e. Usyk vs AJ, SRR at middleweight, Duran, Pac etc.), however this has been corrupted by fighters cutting waterweight the day before fights, junior/super divisions and the abundance of belts hasn't helped. I like Canelo, but Canelo is only really a 2-weight world champ and a 1-weight world champ going by vintage standards
2. So the second way is how well a fighter has cleaned out their division. This also factors in things like title defences and WHO you've beaten. Ali only fought in one division, but defended his belts dozens of times and beat many other HOF fighters. The implication is that if you destroy your division, you're clearly an amazing boxer who COULD compete at higher weight classes. Point 1 vs point 2 is basically Bud vs Spence
3. The final and most subjective way of judging P4P greatness, and this applies quite often to modern fighters who like to stick to one division for a long time and can't get big fights, is the eye-test. It's pretty self-explanatory. It's normally used to support either point 1 or 2

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128836557
Fasted training will burn both fat and muscle. It will burn fat because your body will need a fuel source and it will also ''burn'' muscle because your skeletal muscles are viewed by the body as protein reservoirs. If you want to burn fat slowly and keep your muscles then just do normal workouts with energy foods beforehand. When I go to the gym for 2 hours all of the oats and shit I eat in the morning gets used up. If you want to really deepdive this topic, you need to eat protein even when you're not working out because your body will use skeletal muscle for more important things like your brain, heart, organs, digestive tract, skin etc. I stopped training in October because my job is busy as fuck in November and December, and even though I didn't put on any fat, I lost the definition in my quads, because I had a shitty eating schedule. Also a word of advice don't get hooked on cringey shit like bodybuilding or powerlifting (extreme levels of cringe). ALWAYS box every single gym session, even if it's just a warmup or something

It's almost impossible to be a 'fake' unified champion because there are too many real fighters at every weight class. The sport of boxing asks too much of top level fighters to collect all the belts on accident and actually continue to defend them. If you are a unified champion and have been for a year plus, it's because you are a real fighter.

All that being said I get your underlying concern. Not all weight classes are created equal talent-wise, some have depth and others don't. My personal pound for pound system is designed to remove all emotion/eye-test from p4p lists because opinions on the quality of fighters can shift very rapidly and there is rarely consensus. By focusing on just a few criteria that are close to universally agreed upon in the community (1. The big weight classes 2. Undisputed/unified champions 3. Winning fights as the smaller man) I think you hone in on a pretty hard to argue with list without resorting to purely emotional complaints

And I think it keeps to the literal spirit of pound for pound as in "this boxer, despite not being the most intimidating size-wise, defies the odds to be a dominant champion with the use of their boxing skills"

As I understand it Boehly is making a bet based upon the following:

1)that he can fully refresh his team now while dividing the cost of acquiring those players across an extended period.
2)that with Uefa changing the rules nobody else can exploit this flaw
3)that they will have gotten a team that can legitimately lock in CL football and hopefully win the CL
4)that he can lock in wages at reduced rates since the contract is guaranteed over a zillion years and that some players will take 100k a week over 8 years rather than 250k a week over 3 years
5)because their wage bills per year are reduced it's easier to stay compliant with FFP (lol) and that people will be more willing to buy your old stuff when you want new stuff
6)that CL money will continue to flow in every year

some of the assumptions above are clearly true as there is no more time for other clubs to exploit dividing transfer fees over more than 5 years bur other assumptions seem to be decidedly less likely to pan out.

Still exploitable but to a lesser degree. obviously 100m divided across 5 years is significantly more yearly outlay than 100m across 8 years so the number of transfer you can get in under a finite budget for FFP is reduced when the contract amount per year goes up.

The challenge for Chelsea is that it seems like most of their calculations are predicated on having their revenues for the purposes of FFP including CL moneys which are clearly not guaranteed on a yearly basis with a league as competitive as the PL. Even with the PL apparently increasing to 5 guaranteed spots the addition of Newcastle to the money clubs means more competition for the CL spots.

If Chelsea don't have CL revenues then their "budget" for players while still being FFP compliant is reduced. It's unclear what the impact of being out of compliance with FFP for an extended period would ultimately end up being but it could extend to being banned from european play for some length of time.

It might still be worthwhile for an owner to yolo it and ignore FFP and basically dare Uefa to punish them but thus far it seems like there is enough loopholes for compliance that billionaire toys can still operate more or less with few limits on spending other than what the owner is willing to pay.

My goodness, this thread is filled with so many expressions of absolute masculine insecurity. Gents, this is a man's world. It has always been a man's world. Women are not physically capable of beating men in athletic competition. It is not a question that needs to be considered. There is nothing to be gained from that understanding. No, the best female athletes of today could not beat the best male athletes of any day. So what? Any human with even minimal intelligence already knows that. No one is offended by this knowledge. Certainly no one should derive any flattery from this knowledge either, except maybe the most insecure unformed adult men.

A more interesting question is, could the best athletes of each of the last 10 decades beat their gender-equivalent counterparts of today? Most often, the answer to that question is that it is nearly impossible to compare athletes across generations. It is much better to compare athletes to their contemporaries and measure the separation in talent among the contemporaries and use that measurement to compare athletes across decades.

For example -- In 1920, Babe Ruth led the league with an OPS+ of 255. The next closest was George Sisler with 182 and Joe Jackson with 172. In 2018, Mike Trout led the league with a 198 OPS+. The next closest was Mookie Betts with 186 and JD Martinez with 173. It seems that Babe Ruth was transcendent in his time whereas Trout is a little better than the rest. Would Ruth be a better athlete than Trout today? Impossible to say for certain but Ruth in his time was clearly a level of separation above all others unlike any separation we see today.

I'm not him so I don't know what he thinks, but to what you guys are saying, the odds are supposed to be set within a simulation of 100 times and then slightly slided so that they are always making about 10%. Of course it doesn't always play out that way but the initial odds are set and there are manual ratings taken into account, the part that changes is once the odds are set, the bets coming in will shift the line and odds to maintain that 10%.
It's the same on prob betting sites where lines will change after popular twitter betters put their picks because people dump money into the odds and it automatically shifts thinking something must be wrong. EV betting in nature explains these concepts well because it's people trying to be the /100 situation. As in find bets that have less sharp lines and constantly betting on them because in theory of the machines that are making all the money, when one is wrong you take advantage of it. I don't EV bet but just reading about it teaches you a lot.
Off tangent but this is why WAR is so bad and if there was anyway to prove value it would be atrocious to see how wrong it is. If you ever presented it to anyone who knows about math they would question all of the manual inputs from the fangraph team. They are just made up out of thin air only feeding on it's own system.
If errors like that were made in the manual inputs and evaluation system, betting companies would all lose.

You're generally correct in that you need to be physically strong to play any position, though body types vary. A basic guide:

Offensive positions:
>Quarterback
This is the most skill-based position, so raw physical ability alone won't get you anywhere. Tend to be tall, as that's advantageous for more leverage when throwing, plus having better visibility of the field. There are QB's who are only average height, though.
>Half-back
His job is to receive the ball in hand and run it up the field. Speed/acceleration/ability to sidestep are important. Some are short and strong, for better acceleration and agility, some are bigger, so as to better power through tackles.
>Fullback
Like the half-back, but is less likely to carry the ball (at the NFL-level, you rarely see them running the ball). Bigger than the HB, and more physically aggressive. Sort of a mobile defender for the QB or HB, but who can also run the ball when needed.
>Tight-end
Similar to the Fullback, but usually taller. Needs to be able to catch and run the ball, but also play like a lineman.
>Wide-receiver
Fast, good hands for catching. Sometimes tall, sometimes average height.
>Offensive linemen
The heaviest, strongest players on the team. There are some differences between centers, guards, and tackles, but they're mostly similar.

cont...

Dribbled past is a bit of a nonsense statistic. You can avoid being dribbled past by just backpedalling until you're on top of your goalkeeper. David Luiz would do this all the time much to the team's detriment. You're also more likely to be dribbled past if you're involved in a high press because you're exposing yourself more often by stepping up onto an attacker. The thing is, Jorginho actually rates pretty well as a pressing midfielder. I'd actually say it's something he's very good at. He's also made more interceptions than Partey or Xhaka, suggesting a high level of positional intelligence. And he's absolutely class in possession. The biggest thing we miss when Partey's out is his ability to break lines with diagonals to Saka or Martinelli. Jorginho gives us the ability to do that. It's not all that surprising to me that Arteta has specifically asked for Jorginho after missing out on the club's primary targets. He knows exactly what he's getting with the player, who really fits his overall tactical vision.
